  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for a proof/disproof regarding the sharpness of the De Giorgi recurrence exponent in 3D Navier-Stokes. This requires a deep dive into the literature of regularity theory, specifically checking the 8 known pathways for improving the exponent and verifying if an extremizer exists.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "literature_review_expert",
      "instructions": "Identify the current state of research regarding the De Giorgi recurrence exponent beta = 4/3 for the 3D Navier-Stokes equations. Specifically, confirm if there are any recent papers (post-2010) that claim an improvement or a proof of sharpness. List the 8 standard mathematical routes/strategies typically used to attempt such an improvement in regularity theory."
    },
    {
      "label": "counterexample_specialist",
      "instructions": "Investigate the existence of potential extremizers for the De Giorgi recurrence in the context of 3D Navier-Stokes. Determine if a specific velocity field or pressure distribution can be constructed to show that the 4/3 exponent is the best possible constant, or if such a construction is currently known to be impossible."
    },
    {
      "label": "logic_verifier",
      "instructions": "Analyze the 8 alternative routes identified by the literature expert. For each route, provide a mathematical reason why it fails to improve the exponent beta = 4/3 for the 3D Navier-Stokes equations (e.g., scaling limitations, lack of monotonicity, or pressure term obstructions)."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the literature findings to state the current consensus on the exponent. Use the counterexample analysis to address the extremizer requirement. Use the logic verifier's breakdown to confirm that all 8 alternative routes are blocked. Finally, synthesize these into a binary conclusion (Yes/No) with the required justification."
}

